<font color="#FF0000">TO JEFFERY WINKLER</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 10  5:59:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Jeffery<br>
Alex Hernandez had written roughly 250 words in his last posting.  You had chose to focus on five of them, thus, losing the content of his message.  I appreciate your starting of this thread as I, as well as others, have benefitted from what you and others had left for us.  However, your last posting adds nothing new from your very first one and I doubt Mr. Hernandez will change his views anymore than he will change yours.  But, I still would like to tap into you as a resource if I may.<br><br>
There has been a swing on this thread by some of us trying to gain an understanding of events that happened when some of us vets returned stateside. I have a lot of questions. Perhaps you can indulge me and provide some answers. <br><br>
I have been getting the picture that there were at least two factions of those in the protest community, first, those who wanted troops out of 'Nam to save US soldiers lives and, second, those who wanted the US out of 'Nam because of the moral issue in terms of what was happening to the Vietnamese.  Is this a correct statement or is it an oversimplification.  Were there other factions within the movement?  Of these factions, which were prone to strike out at the returning vets?  <br><br>
I have given examples of a few things that happened to myself after I returned in previous postings.  What influence would you attribute the protest movement, if any, for the general population to be so demonstrative and abusive to returning vets? I have many, many more questions, but this would be a good start.<br><br>
A personal issue I have.  I have trying to find an answer to something that I witness in Vietnam for a long time.  I haven't received any satisying answer.  Perhaps you can shed some light.  In October of '68, we were in the area of Parrots Beak, III Corp, close to the Cambodian border, if not inside it.  Three Cambodian army rangers were flown in to guide us to a village, possibly Mhong.  The village was empty and we soon discovered mass graves containing the villagers.  I have only two clues as to what happened. 1. that this was a Cambodian village due to the rangers presence. 2. The date of this tragedy-October '68.  My question; What was happening inside of Cambodia during that year?  Was Pol Pot a factor then?<br><br>
I apppreciate any answers you, or any others, can provide and thank you.
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


